1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,800
Before we start working on the transformer implementation,

2

00:00:03,800  -->  00:00:05,540
we'll have a quick demo,

3

00:00:05,540  -->  00:00:09,785
where we will cover PyTorch functions that we will use.

4

00:00:09,785  -->  00:00:15,160
The goal of this demo is not to give you a comprehensive overview of PyTorch,

5

00:00:15,160  -->  00:00:18,020
but it is to refresh your PyTorch knowledge.

6

00:00:18,020  -->  00:00:21,200
In case if you don't know some of these functions,

7

00:00:21,200  -->  00:00:24,360
it will make it easier for you to follow it later.

8

00:00:24,360  -->  00:00:27,065
If you're already proficient with PyTorch,

9

00:00:27,065  -->  00:00:29,060
you can just skip this section.

10

00:00:29,060  -->  00:00:32,380
First, we'll see how we can create some random tensors,

11

00:00:32,380  -->  00:00:34,420
which we will use for testing,

12

00:00:34,420  -->  00:00:38,130
and we can do this using the torch rand function.

13

00:00:38,130  -->  00:00:40,320
When we create a random tensor,

14

00:00:40,320  -->  00:00:44,600
we can provide dimensions of a tensor that we want to create.

15

00:00:44,600  -->  00:00:47,820
If we provide a single number like in this case,

16

00:00:47,820  -->  00:00:50,040
it will create a random vector.

17

00:00:50,040  -->  00:00:52,430
If we provide two numbers,

18

00:00:52,430  -->  00:00:56,145
it will create a random tensor 5*5.

19

00:00:56,145  -->  00:00:59,280
The other function the two will use is called ones,

20

00:00:59,280  -->  00:01:05,400
and it allows us to create a tensor of specified dimensions that is filled with ones.

21

00:01:05,400  -->  00:01:08,300
Just as with rant, if we provide a single number,

22

00:01:08,300  -->  00:01:11,720
it will create a vector of size five as in this case,

23

00:01:11,720  -->  00:01:13,840
or if we provide two numbers,

24

00:01:13,840  -->  00:01:17,415
it will create a multi-dimensional tensor filled with ones.

25

00:01:17,415  -->  00:01:20,600
If we need to create a tensor with a sequence of numbers,

26

00:01:20,600  -->  00:01:23,480
we need to use the arrange function.

27

00:01:23,480  -->  00:01:29,270
In this case, it will return a sequence of numbers from 0-9.

28

00:01:29,270  -->  00:01:32,590
One interesting operation that we will need for

29

00:01:32,590  -->  00:01:36,250
transformers is to create a triangular matrix,

30

00:01:36,250  -->  00:01:41,650
where we have values only in the lower triangle of a square matrix.

31

00:01:41,650  -->  00:01:44,910
To do this, we will use the trial function.

32

00:01:44,910  -->  00:01:48,750
The way we need to use this function is we first of all need to create

33

00:01:48,750  -->  00:01:53,135
another tensor and pass this tensor into the trill function.

34

00:01:53,135  -->  00:01:59,290
What it will do, it will set zeros to all positions above the main diagonal.

35

00:01:59,290  -->  00:02:03,870
While implementing transformers will also have to take multiple tensors

36

00:02:03,870  -->  00:02:09,470
and create another tensor that joins values from existing tensors.

37

00:02:09,470  -->  00:02:12,070
We can do this using the CAT function,

38

00:02:12,070  -->  00:02:14,330
which stands for concatenation.

39

00:02:14,330  -->  00:02:17,030
For example, in this particular case,

40

00:02:17,030  -->  00:02:19,550
I have two tensors 2*2,

41

00:02:19,550  -->  00:02:24,830
and I can either concatenate them along the rows or along the columns.

42

00:02:24,830  -->  00:02:27,050
To concatenate them along the rows,

43

00:02:27,050  -->  00:02:32,960
I need to pass them to the CAT function and specify dimension equal to zero.

44

00:02:32,960  -->  00:02:35,140
Or if I do the same thing,

45

00:02:35,140  -->  00:02:37,620
but specify dimension equal to one,

46

00:02:37,620  -->  00:02:41,320
it will concatenate these tensors along the columns.

47

00:02:41,320  -->  00:02:45,480
Now the last transformation that we will cover is called view.

48

00:02:45,480  -->  00:02:50,280
What it allows us to do is to change the shape of a tensor that we have.

49

00:02:50,280  -->  00:02:52,340
For example, in this case,

50

00:02:52,340  -->  00:02:54,660
we have a vector with 12 numbers.

51

00:02:54,660  -->  00:02:56,240
Using the view function,

52

00:02:56,240  -->  00:02:59,440
we can transform it into 3*4 tensor,

53

00:02:59,440  -->  00:03:04,905
all we need to do is to call the view function and specify the new dimensions.

54

00:03:04,905  -->  00:03:11,070
We can also use a view to convert this two-dimensional tensor back into a vector.

55

00:03:11,070  -->  00:03:13,690
In to do this, we need to call the view function

56

00:03:13,690  -->  00:03:17,550
and specify the size of a vector we want to get.
